HW10: The Moving to Opportunity Experiment & Multiple Regression with Inference

Millions of low-income Americans live in high-poverty neighborhoods, which also tend to be racially segregated and sometimes have issues with community violence. While social scientists have long believed a lack of investment in these neighborhoods contributes to negative outcomes for the residents living in them, it is often difficult to establish a causal link between neighborhood conditions and individual outcomes. The Moving to Opportunity (MTO) demonstration was designed to test whether offering housing vouchers to families living in public housing in high-poverty neighborhoods could lead to better experiences and outcomes by providing financial assistance to move to higher income neighborhoods.

Between 1994 and 1998 the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development enrolled 4,604 low-income households from public housing projects in Baltimore, Boston, Chicago, Los Angeles, and New York in MTO, randomly assigning enrolled families in each site to one of three groups: (1) The low-poverty voucher group received special MTO vouchers, which could only be used in census tracts with 1990 poverty rates below 10% and counseling to assist with relocation, (2) the traditional voucher group received regular section 8 vouchers, which they could use anywhere, and (3) the control group, who received no vouchers but continued to qualify for any project-based housing assistance they were entitled to receive. Today we will use the MTO data to learn if being given the opportunity to move to lower-poverty neighborhoods actually improved participants economic and subjective wellbeing. This exercise is based on the following article:

Ludwig, J., Duncan, G.J., Gennetian, L.A., Katz, L.F., Kessler, J.R.K., and Sanbonmatsu, L., 2012. Neighborhood Effects on the Long-Term Well-Being of Low-Income Adults. Science, Vol. 337, Issue 6101, pp.1505-1510.

The file mto3.csv includes the following variables for 3,263 adult participants in the voucher and control groups:

Name Description
group factor with 3 levels: lpv (low-poverty voucher), sec8 (traditional section 8 voucher), and control
econ_ss_zcore Standardized measure of economic self-sufficiency, centered around the control group mean and re-scaled such that the control group mean = 0 and its standard deviation = 1. Measure aggregates several measures of economic self-sufficiency or dependency (earnings, government transfers, employment, etc.)
crime_vic Binary variable, 1 if a member of that household was the victim of a crime in the six months prior to being assigned to the MTO program, 0 otherwise
age Age of the head of household

The data we will use are not the original data, this dataset has been modified to protect participants confidentiality, but the results of our analysis will be consistent with published data on the MTO demonstration. Several of the variables used in this homework are simulated data.

This homework has 61 points.

Question 1 [13 points]

One of the outcomes of interest in this dataset is economic self-sufficiency. The researchers hypothesized that older heads of household would have greater economic self-sufficiency.

1a [5 points]

What linear regression model might be useful for testing this hypothesis? Write the equation for this linear regression model. What is the parameter of interest? What is the estimator (sample summary statistic) for this parameter of interest?

1b [3 points]

What are the Null and Alternative hypotheses? Please use a two-sided hypothesis test.

1c [5 points]

Consider a situation where the manager of the voucher program is planning on using the results of this hypothesis test to determine which households to offer a program to that is intended to improve economic self-sufficiency - all households or only households with younger heads of household.

For this study what is a Type I error and what are its consequences? What is a Type II error and what are its consequences? What alpha level do you suggest for this hypothesis test?

Answer 1

Answer 1a

The linear model that would be useful for testing the researchers hypothesis is: \(E_i = \alpha + \beta*Age_i + \epsilon_i\)

The estimated regression model from observed data is: \(E_i = \hat{\alpha} + \hat{\beta}*Age_i + \hat{\epsilon_i}\)

From this model the parameter of interest is \(\beta\).

The estimator of the parameter of interest is \(\hat{\beta}\).

Answer 1b

The Null Hypothesis is: \(\beta = 0\)

The Alternative Hypothesis is: \(\beta \neq 0\)

Answer 1c

A Type I error is a false positive, in this case it would mean rejecting the null that economic self-sufficiency does not vary by age when the null is true. The consequence in this case of a Type I error is that the manager would offer the program to improve self-sufficiency only to younger heads of household when it is needed just as much in households with older heads of household - so the program would be unfairly limited to younger heads and we would miss the opportunity to improve economic self-sufficiency for middle aged and older headed households.

A Type II error is a false negative, in this case it would be failing to reject the null that economic self-sufficiency does not vary by age when the null is false. The consequence in the case of a Type II error is that the manager offers the program to improve self-sufficiency to all households when the need for it is higher for households with younger heads than households with older heads. Thus the program would be given to those for whom it is less useful and some households that most need it may not be able to get into the program. Could be a waste of program resources.

If you felt the waste of program resources was worse than the missed opportunity, this suggests an \(\alpha\) level of 0.10.

If you felt that the missed opportunity and unfair limiting of program resources was worse than non-optimal targeting of resources, this suggests an an \(\alpha\) level of 0.01.

If you felt that the two consequences were about equally bad, this suggests an \(\alpha\) level of 0.05.

Answer 2d

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(mod1, c(1, 2))
hist(resid(mod1))
boxplot(resid(mod1), ylab = "Residuals Mod1")

The linearity assumption is not violated because the residual plot appears to have a mean residual of zero across the entire range of fitted values as we look from left to right. The constant variance assumption is also not violated because the variance or spread of the residuals appears to be more or less equal across the range of fitted values as we look from left to right.

We find some evidence for violations of the normality assumption from the QQ plot, because the tails of the distribution of residuals do not match the theoretical quantiles exactly. As the violations are restricted to the tails of the distribution and hence are mild and the data set is large (several thousand observations), it is safe to ignore this violation and proceed assuming that the inferences about the regression results are approximately accurate. In addition, the histogram and boxplot show a mound shaped symmetric distribution. There are outliers but they are on both ends of the distribution.

Answer 2e

The linearity assumption not being violated indicates that the y-intercept and slope estimates are unbiased and useful for describing the relationship between age and mean economic self-sufficiency. It also indicates that the r-squared estimate is unbiased and meaningful.

The constant variance assumption not being violated indicates that the RMSE estimate is meaningful.

The normality assumptions approximately holding with large data (along with the constant variance assumption) indicates that the standard error estimates for beta-hat and alpha-hat are unbiased, the sampling distributions for beta-hat and alpha-hat are (or are well approximated by) a t-distribution with n 2 degrees of freedom.

Question 4 [9 pts]

Question 4a [2 points]

Create a dichotomous lpv variable that takes the value 1 for all households with a low poverty voucher and takes the value 0 for all other households. The researchers also hypothesize that the low poverty voucher will improve economic self-sufficiency (relative to control and Section 8 groups combined - these can be referred to as usual housing support). For this hypothesis, state the specific causal question.

Question 4b [4 points]

State the potential outcomes for a single household. What linear regression model might be useful to test this hypothesis (include age as a covariate in the model and the dichotomous lpv variable)? What is the parameter of interest?

Question 4c [3 points]

What are the null and alternative hypotheses? Use a two-sided hypothesis test.

Answer 4

Answer 4a

mto3$lpv <- mto3$group == "lpv"

The causal question is ``what is the effect of receiving the low poverty voucher relative to usual housing support on economic self-sufficiency (holding age constant) for eligible low income families?"

Answer 4b

Potential outcomes for a single household are what that households economic self-sufficiency score would be if they received a low poverty voucher and what that same households economic self-sufficiency score would be with usual housing support.

We could test the researchers hypothesis using a linear regression model that regresses economic self-sufficiency (the outcome) on a dichotomous variable indicating whether a household received the lpv relative to usual housing support, as well as any number of covariates that may help explain economic self-sufficiency (e.g., age). \(E_i = \alpha + \beta_1*Age_i +\beta_2*LPV_i +\epsilon_i\)

The parameter of interest here is the true value of the coefficient on lpv (\(\beta_2\)).

Answer 4c

The null hypothesis is that the true coefficient on lpv is zero, \(\beta_2 = 0\), and the two-sdied alternative hypothesis is that the true coefficient on lpv is not equal to zero, \(\beta_2 \neq 0\).

The linearity assumption is not violated because in the residual plot the residuals appear to have a mean of zero across the entire range of fitted values as we look from left to right.

The constant variance assumption is also not violated because the variance or spread of the residuals appears to be more or less equal across the range of fitted values as we look from left to right.

We find some evidence for violations of the normality assumption from the QQ plot, because the tails of the distribution of residuals do not match the theoretical quantiles exactly. However the histrogram shows a mound shaped mostly symmetric distribution ) perhaps some slight low skew. The boxplot shows also suggests symmetry and shows some outliers at both the ends of the distribution. As the violations are restricted to the tails of the distribution and hence are mild and the data set is large (several thousand observations), it is safe to ignore this violation and proceed with analyzing the inferences regarding the regression results.

The linearity assumption not being violated indicates that the y-intercept and slope estimates are unbiased and useful for describing the relationship between the low poverty voucher, age, and economic self-sufficiency. It also indicates that the RMSE and r-squared estimates are unbiased although the RMSE may not be meaningful.

The constant variance assumption not being violated indicates that the RMSE estimate is meaningful.

The normality assumptions approximately holding with large data (along with the constant variance holding) indicates that the standard error estimates for beta-hat and alpha-hat are unbiased and the sampling distributions for beta-hat and alpha-hat are (or are well approximated by) a t-distribution with n 3 degrees of freedom.

Answer 5b

R-squared: 69% of variation in economic self-sufficiency is accounted for by its linear relationship with age and treatment. This is only very slightly higher than the model with only age as a predictor suggesting that treatment is not a strong predictor of economic self-sufficiency particularly in comparison to how predictive age is.

RMSE: The square root of the average of squared differences between observed and fitted values is 0.558, where the units are the same as the outcome variable - or less technically, the average distance peoples individual economic self-sufficiency is away from the mean of those of their age and treatment group. This is very slightly smaller than the RMSE from the model with only age as a predictor suggesting that knowing treatment group doesnt reduce our uncertainty about someones economic self-sufficiency level much at all.

Slope coefficient on age: The slope coefficient on age is 0.06, indicating that a one-year increase in age is associated with a 0.06 increase in average economic self-sufficiency or equivalently, a 10-year increase in age is associated with a 0.6 increase in average economic self-sufficiency.

Answer 5c

A figure showing the estimated multiple linear regression in this question will have two parallel lines, one for those with the low poverty voucher, and one without, which will have the same slope, but will be separated by a shift which corresponds to the coefficient on lpv in the model we ran in this question. The low poverty voucher group line is above the usual housing support line. Both lines are upwardly sloping (and parallel) with increasing age of head of household. This distance between the two up-sloping parallel lines (0.16) is the estimated average treatment effect (controlling for age) with the lvp line above the usual housing support line.

Answer 5d

p-value for the coefficient on lpv: The p-value for the coefficient on lpv is very small. The p-value indicates the probability that this result, or one any farther from the null, occurred by chance under the null hypothesis that the true coefficient is zero. We would therefore reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative at any common significance level in favor of the alternative (0.10, 0.05, 0.01, 0.001). Note that the default in R is to give the p-value for the two-sided hypothesis test.

Answer 6

Answer 6a

The linear regression model that could be used to test this hypothesis is:

\(E_i = \alpha + \beta_1*Age_i +\beta_2*LPV_i +\beta_3*Age_i*LPV_i +\epsilon_i\)

From this model, the parameter of interest is \(\beta_3\).

The Null Hypothesis is \(\beta_3 = 0\) The Alternative Hypothesis is \(\beta_3 \neq 0\)

Answer 6b

All three model assumptions hold:

The linearity assumption is not violated because in the residual plot the residuals appear to have a mean of zero across the entire range of fitted values as we look from left to right.

The constant variance assumption is also not violated because the variance or spread of the residuals appears to be more or less equal across the range of fitted values as we look from left to right.

We find some evidence for violations of the normality assumption from the QQ plot, because the tails of the distribution of residuals do not match the theoretical quantiles exactly. However the histrogram shows a mound shaped mostly symmetric distribution ) perhaps some slight low skew. The boxplot shows also suggests symmetry and shows some outliers at both the ends of the distribution. As the violations are restricted to the tails of the distribution and hence are mild and the data set is large (several thousand observations), it is safe to ignore this violation and proceed with analyzing the inferences regarding the regression results.

The estimated coefficient on the interaction term is 0.975 standard errors away from the Null value of zero. Under the null hypothesis obtaining a value this far or any farther from zero just by chance is 0.330. We do not reject the Null with an \(\alpha\) level of 0.10. The implications of this result for the researchers hypothesis is that we cannot reject that the low poverty voucher (relative to usual housing support) has the same average impact on economic self-sufficiency for households whose head of household are different ages.
